Since you’re all out grilling burgers today ….. “One Thing is True”. About 50 x 72 on unprimed canvas. People often ask about the hamburger in so many works. Icons are ingrained in my psyche. Many of you probably know that my “schooling” is a byproduct of a degree in Graphic Design. That being said logos and timeless trademarks are always in the back of my little noggin. I’ve always found the Michelin Man one of the most iconic. He’s survived over a hundred years of advertising and no doubt that under countless changes of the guard. I think he’s here to say and deserves respect.  And yea, I’m aware that many of you will simply see “Marshmallow Man”. You see what you want to see and you feel what you want to feel. That’s the point in some works. Chill. And btw:  my Dallas Design District gallery space is now open by appointment only. Don’t worry, we won’t bite, we just have a lot of plates spinning so let us know when you want to visit. 214-748-5118. In Dallas I’m also represented by the In Detail group in the Dallas World Trade Center so if you’re coming for market, your rep can arrange a visit as well. As always, I offer special pricing to the trade but you must submit your credentials on the www.design-legacy.Com website prior to having access to such. My “Reverence Series” is anything but. And speaking of butts, I give you “Perseus, Oh Hell No!” .  I’ve collected paper ephemera most of my life. The collection led me to a degree in graphic design as well as to the drafting of my own company ( @design_legacy ) which features inspiration from the myriad originals in my collection numbering over 10,000 pieces to date. I particularly love religious and mythological imagery.  The original book plate for this one is from the 17th century.  Perseus particularly was a fascination of mine in Greek mythology. The slayer of bad things, Medusa whose head he holds here among those. As a kid I had nightmares about the Michelin Man so I decided to rid myself of that for once and for all. Or maybe not as he keeps appearing in these graphic works. This piece is available in my archival series in canvas or paper form. Always signed. Reach out to a gallery in your area or we can connect you with a simple screen shot of anything of interest via e-mail. Info@koneal.com should you be so inclined. True story. The tiny town I’m from is nickname central, or rather my dad and uncle had a nickname for everyone in the town. We weren’t well-to-do anything. We also weren’t NEAR anything of consequence in fine dining other than the local and now legendary “Malt Shop” so eating out wasn’t a frequent event for many reasons. When I would travel in the big rigs with my Grandad he would humor me to eat my favorite meal of all (you all know the hamburger story) at Kips. The iconic “Big Boy” was the siren to a ten or so year-old boy but the funny thing is at first I thought that our local “Big Boy” owned the joint!  My Grandad set me straight on that one but I still get a giggle out of any mention of “Big Boy”. Small town sentimentality…..the Force is strong with that.
